2 TITL bush declaration
2 _TEXT The Historical Significance of the Bush Declaration   On March 22, 17
3 CONC 7 5, thirty-four men gathered in a small tavern to sign the historic B
3 CONC us h Declaration. In this short text, these unique individuals pledge
3 CONC d th eir lives and fortune to support freedom.  Genealogist General, H
3 CONC enr y C. Peden, Jr. describes the historical context of the Bush Decla
3 CONC rati on in this way:  The Bush Declaration is a document signed by 3
3 CONC 4 dul y elected citizens in Harford County, Maryland on March 22, 1775
3 CONC . At t hat time the county seat was Harford Town, or Bush (so named fo
3 CONC r its l ocation in the "bush country" as compared to most colonial tow
3 CONC ns on th e waterfront, that is, Chesapeake Bay). Harford County had be
3 CONC en separa ted from Baltimore County just a year earlier and in the int
3 CONC erim ther e was considerable patriotic fervor against the British an
3 CONC d their bloc kade of Boston (and other problems, like taxation). Thi
3 CONC s committee i n Harford County decided to show their support for Bosto
3 CONC n and their di sdain for King George by signing this document "at th
3 CONC e risque of thei r lives and fortunes." It has been characterized as t
3 CONC he first Declarat ion of Independence and was signed just three week
3 CONC s prior to the Battl es of Lexington and Concord which signaled the be
3 CONC ginning of the Americ an Revolution.
