2 TITL Gurdon-Saltonstall
2 _TEXT Gurdon Saltonstall (27 March 1666, Haverhill, Massachusetts, – 20 Sep
3 CONC t ember 1724, New London, Connecticut) was Governor of the Colony of C
3 CONC on necticut from 1708 to 1724. Born into a distinguished family, Salto
3 CONC nst all became an accomplished and eminent Connecticut pastor before b
3 CONC ein g appointed the colony's governor.      Early Life and Pastor    S
3 CONC alto nstall was the son of Nathaniel and Elizabeth (Ward) Saltonstall
3 CONC , a pr ominent north Massachusetts family active in Massachusetts poli
3 CONC tics si nce the 1630s. He received his bachelor's degree in 1684 fro
3 CONC m Harvar d Divinity School, where he studied theology, and was awarde
3 CONC d his mast ers degree in 1687.[1] It was at this time that Saltonstal
3 CONC l first prea ched at First Christ Church in New London where he impres
3 CONC sed congregan ts enough to warrant his appointment as the town's sol
3 CONC e pastor.  Salto nstall soon grew close to the Connecticut's governor
3 CONC , Fitz-John Winthr op and became not simply an adviser in spiritual ma
3 CONC tters, but in civi l ones as well.  When Governor Winthrop's health fa
3 CONC iled him, Saltonsta ll eventually began assuming executive responsibil
3 CONC ities in the Governo r's absence.  He was married to Mary Whittingham
3 CONC e (d. 1730), a grandda ughter of Mayor of New York John Lawrence (1618
3 CONC -1699).      Politica l Career    Upon Governor Winthrop's death in 17
3 CONC 07, Saltonstall was ap pointed governor of the Colony of Connecticut b
3 CONC y a special session o f the legislature,  a decision that sparked som
3 CONC e outcry because of Sal tonstall's status as clergy. Saltonstall himse
3 CONC lf was hesitant to leav e his Church and take on the position of Gover
3 CONC nor, which prompted th e state Assembly to aid his First Church of Chr
3 CONC ist in finding a replac ement pastor. His selection approved by voter
3 CONC s in May of that year, ho wever, Saltonstall continued to be re-electe
3 CONC d annually until his death . Governor was just one of the influentia
3 CONC l positions held by Saltonsta ll, as he was appointed commander of th
3 CONC e Connecticut militia and Chie f Justice of its Superior Court.   Salt
3 CONC onstall believed strongly in th e power of traditional authority, a tr
3 CONC ademark of his time as clergyma n and governor.  He was wholly intoler
3 CONC ant of divergent Christian sects , and favored the enjoining of Churc
3 CONC h and government into what he imag ined would be a more effective syst
3 CONC em, an idea enumerated in the Saybr ook Platform, a proposal mainly as
3 CONC cribed to him. The governor also fou nd opposition to his government
3 CONC , or dispute within it to be contemptib le, and frequently threatene
3 CONC d to resign if such discord was not discon tinued.     Saltonstall's s
3 CONC upport of established authority is also see n in his decision-making t
3 CONC hroughout Queen Anne's War, the second Frenc h and Indian War over con
3 CONC trol of North America. The governor was an lo yal supporter of the Bri
3 CONC tish cause, seeking to reduce colony oppositio n to the war, and aide
3 CONC d Queen Anne by increasing the recruitment and e quipment of Connectic
3 CONC ut militiamen sent to battle French forces. The C onnecticut soldier
3 CONC s would eventually total 4,000 men, a sizable portio n of the colony'
3 CONC s 17,000 people. Because of the war's heavy costs, Con necticut's fisc
3 CONC al situation deteriorated, but Saltonstall's enthusiast ic support o
3 CONC f the Crown won the state much improved relations with Gre at Britain
3 CONC , recently renamed the United Kingdom.     The governor work ed closel
3 CONC y with Massachusetts Bay Colony governor, Joseph Dudley, in p eacefull
3 CONC y resolving the problem of the "Equivalent Lands," just one o f many b
3 CONC order disputes demanding his attention.
